Sensex may open above 29,000, Nifty race towards 9,000 after Modi’s UP win 
14-3-2017 
After the Bharatiya Janata Party’s resounding victory in Uttar Pradesh, Indian markets are set to open higher on Tuesday, with Nifty seen surging towards the 9,000-level and Sensex breaching 29,000-level on expectations of faster reforms even as investors are nervous ahead of the US Federal Reserve policy review.

On Friday, the Sensex closed flat at 28,946 while Nifty finished at 8,934.55. Investors expect Nifty may soon scale all-time high of 9,119 and Sensex touch 30,000-mark.

On Saturday, the BJP won more than 300 out of the 403 seats in the assembly elections of India’s largest state Uttar Pradesh, which enhances chances of Prime Minister Narendra Modi’s second term at the Centre and ensures political stability and faster reforms including the roll out of Goods and Services Tax, passage of labour and land acquisition bills.

On Tuesday, Asian markets opened mixed with the MSCI’s broadest index of Asia-Pacific shares outside Japan flat in early trade. Japan’s Nikkei was down 0.14% while Hang Seng was up 0.1%, Kospi 0.5% and Shanghai 0.25%.

Wall Street closed weaker as the Dow Jones Industrial Average ended down 0.1% but Nasdaq was up 0.24% and S&P flat.

The dollar gained on Fed rate hike expectation while euro fell after British Parliament cleared Prime Minister Theresa May’s Brexit plan.

The dollar index against a group of major currencies gained 0.1% with the greenback gaining 0.1% against the yen. The euro was down 0.1% at about $1.065. 
